kind of taking over right now just because I'm in the middle of summer in Colorado. But

00:01:22.699 --> 00:01:28.459
other than that, you know, I spend a lot of time outdoors. So hiking, climbing, camping

00:01:28.459 --> 00:01:37.779
is a big part of my life. Also really into playing guitar. I've been learning drums over

00:01:37.779 --> 00:01:44.180
the last few years. I'm kind of a musician first before I ever got into math or data

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:50.379
or anything like that. Maybe I always try to think of it, I'm like, why do I like number

00:01:50.379 --> 00:01:54.980
patterns so much? I think it's just because I studied guitar tabs so much in middle school

00:01:54.980 --> 00:02:00.540
and high school, just to learn new songs. And then I started noticing number patterns

00:02:00.540 --> 00:02:08.660
and I was like, oh, I'm going to get into math. But other hobbies, I kind of went back

00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:16.779
and forth from homebrewing and doing other stuff like that. I have two sons, so three

00:02:16.779 --> 00:02:24.940
in one. So mostly playing with monster trucks and Hot Wheels in my free time. And then,

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:32.899
you know, I'm also, like, been working in open source software a little bit here and

00:02:32.899 --> 00:02:38.699
there, kind of building packages out in R, posting those on GitHub and just kind of talking

00:02:38.699 --> 00:02:45.779
about it on Blue Sky or X or something like that. So kind of like a hobby of many hobbies.

00:02:46.779 --> 00:02:53.500
And then, kind of goes back to my team, I think we're all kind of full stack data scientists.

00:02:53.500 --> 00:03:00.100
So we all do a little bit of shiny, do a little bit of data engineering, do some machine learning

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:01.619
and everything in between.

00:03:01.619 --> 00:03:08.820
Awesome. Well, I want to dig in a little bit to what you do and give everybody a little

00:03:08.820 --> 00:03:15.059
bit of context so that they can ask good questions in Slido. Because not everybody kind of knows

00:03:15.059 --> 00:03:23.580
a lot about energy markets or the energy industry. And when I learned what you do,

00:03:23.580 --> 00:03:27.100
I was shocked because you told me that your team oversees over a thousand models. And

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:32.660
I was like, excuse me, what? Did you just, like, was that a verbal typo? Like more than

00:03:32.660 --> 00:03:36.979
a thousand models? Why do you need that? But then you explained it to me and it made perfect

00:03:36.979 --> 00:03:39.380
sense. So I'd love it if you could talk a little bit about that.

00:03:39.380 --> 00:03:47.779
Yeah, totally. Yeah. So, like, we're in wholesale energy. So, like, ACES is an alliance of cooperatives

00:03:47.779 --> 00:03:54.899
for energy services. We have a whole kind of menu of services that we offer from front

00:03:54.899 --> 00:04:01.820
office to back office. I'm in front office. I support our portfolio management team, our

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:08.139
portfolio strategy team, our portfolio modeling team. We also have resource planning and fundamentals

00:04:08.139 --> 00:04:13.139
and a capacity team. And then we kind of, like, bounce ideas back and forth with the

00:04:13.139 --> 00:04:17.859
transmission team. So there's, like, all these different teams that are, like, supporting

00:04:17.859 --> 00:04:24.420
these co-ops. And really, we're trying to lower their variable costs, but also understand

00:04:24.420 --> 00:04:30.859
the risk associated with the portfolio. And, like, you would think you could set up, like,

00:04:30.859 --> 00:04:39.220
one model, but, like, just like the whole fact that the United States is split up into

00:04:39.220 --> 00:04:45.540
different ISOs and they have different regulations, they have different resource mix, they – each

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:50.700
one of our portfolios could be in a different area of that ISO, and that brings on different

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:57.820
challenges. So, you know, we're simulating over 40 portfolios, and then each of those

00:04:57.820 --> 00:05:03.100
have their own – maybe more than one load. And whenever I say load, I guess it's – so,

00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:06.739
like, load is being, like, a demand on the system. So it's kind of a supply and demand

00:05:06.739 --> 00:05:13.579
problem. And you need to serve this load. And they might be in an area of the country

00:05:13.579 --> 00:05:16.700
that has tons of wind. They might be in an area of the country that's, like, natural

00:05:16.700 --> 00:05:22.940
gas and solar and battery. And all of these things create different issues with the way

00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:26.540
that you can kind of create a supply mix to serve that load.

00:05:26.859 --> 00:05:29.739
We have a quick question to interject. What's ISO?

00:05:31.019 --> 00:05:36.700
Yeah, it's an independent system operator. There's a lot of acronyms in energy. So I'll

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:40.700
try not to say too many, but please stop me if I do. Yeah.

00:05:41.660 --> 00:05:49.019
So I think that the gist is there is so much variation across a region, across a town,

00:05:49.739 --> 00:05:57.579
between towns, not only in the energy that they demand, but also the energy that is available

00:05:57.579 --> 00:06:02.140
to be consumed, right? So you've got to model – you've got to model, for example,

00:06:02.140 --> 00:06:06.779
the San Antonio metropolitan area where I live. Like, how much are we going to need?

00:06:06.779 --> 00:06:09.980
And you go out a pretty far time horizon, like 25 years, right?

00:06:10.700 --> 00:06:15.579
Yeah, yeah. So whether you regulate it or not, you kind of want to have an idea of what's

00:06:15.579 --> 00:06:20.940
going to happen in the next hour. Or then you start thinking, you're like, I want to know what's

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:27.179
going to happen tomorrow, so there's a day ahead market. And then when you're doing financial

00:06:27.179 --> 00:06:32.540
planning and analysis, you want to know what happens next year. But then when you're talking

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:39.820
to a city council or talking about putting new steel in the ground, and you're trying to defend

00:06:39.820 --> 00:06:45.260
whether or not to build a new combustion turbine in this area of the country,

00:06:45.899 --> 00:06:51.260
you kind of need to simulate out 25 years to understand what the hourly price shapes would be,

00:06:51.899 --> 00:06:57.179
what the hourly demand might be in that area, what the supply mix is going to be, and then

00:06:57.739 --> 00:07:03.980
whether or not that particular hedge or new generator would even be useful in that area

00:07:03.980 --> 00:07:10.220
of the country. So you start like, I want to know what happens in the next five minutes,

00:07:10.220 --> 00:07:15.420
the next hour. I want to plan for tomorrow. And then you start getting everyone in on the company,

00:07:15.420 --> 00:07:22.380
and you're like, okay, well, we need to plan years ahead of time. And the independent system

00:07:22.380 --> 00:07:27.579
operator is also a market, so it's trying to also help that planning. But there's also

00:07:28.459 --> 00:07:33.899
non-ISO areas of the United States too. So regardless, you kind of don't want to have

00:07:33.899 --> 00:07:39.660
a blackout. So how do we mitigate that? And also- What happened in Texas in 2021?

00:07:40.220 --> 00:07:46.459
Yeah, yeah. You don't want to run out of supply when there's high demand. So that's a huge issue,

00:07:47.179 --> 00:07:50.459
especially if demand is increasing across the United States.

00:07:52.220 --> 00:07:56.299
One more context-building thing that Frank had told me the last time I talked to him that I

00:07:56.299 --> 00:08:02.059
thought was really interesting was that some regions have surplus energy, and that the energy

00:08:02.059 --> 00:08:09.420
price can actually be negative. You could have a price for energy that is zero. That kind of blew

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:15.579
my mind a little bit. If there's an area where there is a bunch of wind electricity being

00:08:15.579 --> 00:08:21.500
generated, but there aren't a lot of homes there consuming that power, where does that power go?

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:28.380
And how do you make sure that it ends up where there are high population density areas that

00:08:28.380 --> 00:08:31.500
really need that? That's a really tough problem to solve, isn't it?

00:08:32.059 --> 00:08:41.419
Yeah, yeah. And you can think of this as not anyone's fault, but wind just blows more in

00:08:42.219 --> 00:08:48.299
Kansas, Oklahoma, Minnesota, but not a lot of people are in those areas. So then you have to

00:08:48.299 --> 00:08:56.700
build transmission to get it to the demand. So, Kansas City being really far away from

00:08:56.700 --> 00:09:03.900
western Kansas where you see tons of wind farms, so how do you get that wind power over to the

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:12.460
people? And within the markets, it's designed in a way so it's going to desensitize supply where

00:09:12.460 --> 00:09:16.619
there's already tons of supply and no demand. So, you'll see prices go negative around

00:09:17.500 --> 00:09:22.859
renewable generation where there's a pocket of renewables and they haven't quite built out the

00:09:22.859 --> 00:09:29.179
transmission. So, yeah, you have to – you start simulating, you come up with like a vanilla model,

00:09:29.179 --> 00:09:33.179
and it starts to work for everywhere, and then you start running into these edge cases and you

00:09:33.179 --> 00:09:39.979
have to build new models to handle these different nodes. So, that's where you end up thinking I have

00:09:39.979 --> 00:09:44.219
one model to simulate top-down. I'm just thinking total load of the system,

00:09:45.179 --> 00:09:51.260
total wind of the system, total solar penetration of the system. And then you're like, okay, I got

00:09:51.260 --> 00:09:57.419
a pretty good net load model for the entire system. But then you start getting into nuances

00:09:57.419 --> 00:10:03.979
of, hey, I need to simulate this one node for this portfolio that happens to be a wind turbine

00:10:03.979 --> 00:10:08.780
surrounded by other wind turbines. And you're like, how do I create a price shape for that location?

00:10:09.739 --> 00:10:19.179
It can be negative quite often. So, yeah, there is this really interesting markets plus energy,

00:10:19.179 --> 00:10:23.020
plus physics, plus engineering that all goes into it. Yeah.

00:10:23.020 --> 00:10:29.500
Yeah. Yeah. And for anybody wondering, Frank's background is physics, but this does seem like

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:36.380
a lot of finance, economics, mechanical engineering even, a little bit in there,

00:10:36.380 --> 00:10:39.580
electrical engineering. Well, we have so many good questions in the slide out. They are

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:43.260
stacking up like crazy. So, let's see if we can get through some of them. Thank you, everybody,

00:10:43.260 --> 00:10:47.500
for asking your amazing questions. And the one that I see that I think would be great to start

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:52.940
with is from Edward Leland. Edward, are you available to unmute and ask your question live?

00:10:52.940 --> 00:10:57.979
If so, I think it's going to cover a couple of other questions. I know Arsenis had asked one that

00:10:57.979 --> 00:11:03.099
was really sort of in the same line. And so, I might add on a little bit of Arsenis's teeters.

00:11:03.979 --> 00:11:10.619
All right. Yeah. Sounds good. Hey, I'm also a physics background person. I was my undergrad.

00:11:10.619 --> 00:11:15.820
I was a double major in physics comp sci. Good to know other people got out of physics and are

00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:22.219
doing comp sci stuff. I don't know. It broke my brain. Anyway, sorry. Here's the question.

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:28.700
What are your go-to models for analysis in your field? Because you got like 1,000 plus.

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:33.820
Do you have to evaluate every problem individually, or do you have a class

00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:37.979
or type of models that you get to use for a lot of different applications?

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:40.299
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:11:47.179 --> 00:11:54.059
I think you have a class by maybe fuel resource type. So, we have a few engineering models for

00:11:54.059 --> 00:11:59.979
wind turbines, and that might change depending on what kind of turbine lane is on the particular

00:12:02.219 --> 00:12:10.140
wind farm or what the manufacturer is. Same with solar, depending on where it's located

00:12:10.140 --> 00:12:16.299
and you have an understanding of the kind of solar irradiance in that area and what kind of panel it

00:12:16.299 --> 00:12:23.419
is. We have pretty good engineering models for those as well. When it comes to kind of coming

00:12:23.419 --> 00:12:33.739
up with like demand profiles and price shapes, those can – you can start trying a few statistical

00:12:33.739 --> 00:12:40.380
methods, but I think you end up kind of doing a few different machine learning methods. So, that

00:12:42.380 --> 00:12:48.940
tree-based, rule-based, linear models, polynomial models, those work pretty well depending on how

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:54.780
you kind of feature engineer. So, I think that's kind of where it really helps to work with the

00:12:54.780 --> 00:13:00.140
business. So, like, that's where my team's kind of working with all these portfolio strategists,

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:05.900
portfolio management teams, where they might see and have a hunch on, like, hey, this is what's

00:13:05.900 --> 00:13:11.580
driving this congestion. I think that's what's driving this negative pricing. And then you're

00:13:11.580 --> 00:13:15.900
working with them and kind of feed that into the model, and then the model picks up on the

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:25.580
price patterns. So, that's kind of our methodology. My team, we're using tiny models for

00:13:26.539 --> 00:13:33.580
80 percent, 90 percent of the models that we're building, doing everything from scratch. So, yeah.

00:13:33.580 --> 00:13:35.659
That's awesome.

00:13:35.659 --> 00:13:45.020
Yeah. Yeah, there's a few other resources in Python, Julia and R. NREL, they make a lot of

00:13:45.020 --> 00:13:52.380
toolkits. And then when you're – sometimes I talk – I say model a lot, so I'm always saying, like,

00:13:52.380 --> 00:13:58.140
regression model, but then there's the portfolio modelers that have a portfolio model. And then

00:13:58.140 --> 00:14:02.380
I'm talking to IT about models, and they're, like, talking data model, and I'm like, okay,

00:14:02.380 --> 00:14:07.580
I'm talking about regression model here. The portfolio modeling team has their own software

00:14:07.580 --> 00:14:13.820
as well. And that's kind of putting together all of the PNLs off of the loads and the supplies and

00:14:13.820 --> 00:14:17.739
stacking that and coming up with the average variable cost and risk associated with it.

00:14:17.739 --> 00:14:22.460
Yeah, lots and lots of the word model getting used in different terms. Well, I wanted to tack

00:14:22.460 --> 00:14:27.260
on Ari's question. I hope you don't mind if I grab some of the bits of your question and ask

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:33.659
them here. Okay, good. Because he had asked in the same vein, like, do you tend to use traditional

00:14:33.659 --> 00:14:40.299
stochastic models for time series analysis or more of the recent ML methods in time series analysis?

00:14:40.299 --> 00:14:45.659
I'm also curious about whether you have used LSTM, which is long short-term memory,

00:14:45.659 --> 00:14:51.099
for longer-term predictions and how that has performed. Yeah, yeah, that's a great question.

00:14:55.500 --> 00:15:03.419
You know, we've moved away from Monte Carlo. So, I would say 10 years ago, I was doing a lot of

00:15:03.419 --> 00:15:12.059
Monte Carlo stochastic simulation. So, I think the problem is like with when you start introducing

00:15:12.059 --> 00:15:19.739
when you're in a transitional time. So, you went from just like, all right, is coal or is natural

00:15:19.739 --> 00:15:26.859
gas cheaper? Then we know which plant is going to run and we can kind of simulate those commodities

00:15:26.859 --> 00:15:32.460
and come up multiplying by the heat rate of that power plant, come up with a power price.

00:15:33.419 --> 00:15:39.099
And you're kind of chasing that. Then now we have like, we started introducing wind, it's taking

00:15:39.099 --> 00:15:44.619
over like 50% of the world and then you start adding solar and then batteries. And then you

00:15:44.619 --> 00:15:51.020
have like these price shapes that just for Monte Carlo simulation are just the tails are too fat

00:15:51.020 --> 00:15:59.340
and long. So, we start doing machine learning everywhere for stochastics. So, starting with,

00:16:00.299 --> 00:16:06.619
you can start really simple, just take like one weather day and just trying to understand like

00:16:06.619 --> 00:16:15.419
what one weather day, what are the options for a wind profile, a solar profile, and a load profile.

00:16:15.979 --> 00:16:19.580
And then you can come up with the net load and the subsequent price shape. So,

00:16:22.059 --> 00:16:28.219
then I say that one weather day, then you can just do that over a thousand times and you have a

00:16:28.219 --> 00:16:35.260
thousand load solar and wind shapes. So, I think that's kind of like what we're moving towards as

00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:41.419
an industry standard. I see that across other companies. There's at least like 7 out of the

00:16:41.419 --> 00:16:47.419
10 companies that I know are moving towards that are already there. And then that's where we are,

00:16:47.419 --> 00:16:55.419
and we're providing the service for over 45, 46 energy companies across the United States.

00:16:55.419 --> 00:17:01.820
So, I think everyone's more inclined to like saying like a billion dollar extreme weather

00:17:01.820 --> 00:17:08.619
event disasters keeps increasing over time. That's like, I think all the risk is associated with

00:17:08.619 --> 00:17:15.900
weather. So, trying to understand that and starting from that framework instead of just a simple

00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:21.260
Monte Carlo simulation. That's a great question. And then LSTMs, we don't use those.

00:17:21.979 --> 00:17:29.900
I work with Purdue and their geodata science department on testing out a few in MISO.

00:17:31.420 --> 00:17:38.459
Just the complexity and then the computation time. And then I just don't think for us,

00:17:39.260 --> 00:17:46.939
we don't have our data like normalized and stationary enough for that to be scalable

00:17:46.939 --> 00:17:52.699
across all the data. A tree-based model or root-based models better for that, in my opinion.

00:17:53.979 --> 00:17:57.660
Very good to know. This is really good information for anyone who's like,

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:02.540
where can I do this in practice? Like I learned all these things in grad school or undergrad,

00:18:02.540 --> 00:18:06.699
and I kind of want to do this. The energy industry might be a place for you, right?

00:18:07.660 --> 00:18:13.739
We had a couple of questions in the Slido that were about like what is a full-stack data scientist?

00:18:13.739 --> 00:18:19.260
I think Noor had asked and Abigail as well. Abigail has a little asterisk by her saying like,

00:18:19.260 --> 00:18:24.939
hey, I can't ask this right now. So, I'm going to ask it for her. But I wanted to give sort of

00:18:24.939 --> 00:18:29.420
you the chance to talk a little bit about your background as well because you told me

00:18:30.780 --> 00:18:35.099
that you learned. This is such a backward experience from what I normally see

00:18:35.099 --> 00:18:40.939
for everybody. You learned like Python in undergrad. You got out into industry and

00:18:41.660 --> 00:18:45.660
you learned Excel in industry. You were like confronted with huge Excel files.

00:18:45.660 --> 00:18:51.500
And then your IT department asked you if you know R. Now, every IT department that I have

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:57.260
ever talked to, I have been trying to convince them to let me work in R, not the other way around.

00:18:57.260 --> 00:19:02.859
So, if you could talk a little bit about how that happened for you. And then the question from

00:19:02.859 --> 00:19:07.979
Abigail and I think from Noor as well was like, what does full-stack data scientist mean to you?

00:19:08.780 --> 00:19:12.939
How do you explain that you're a full-stack data scientist to someone without confusing them?

00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:19.500
What's the overlap between a full-stack data scientist and something like an NL engineer

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:26.939
or a data engineer? Yeah. Yeah. Those are all great questions. I was scrolling through here

00:19:26.939 --> 00:19:34.859
and I didn't realize how many people were here. But I was looking for the person that recommended

00:19:34.859 --> 00:19:39.979
R, see if he was in here. I don't think he is. He might be. I could have skipped over his name.

00:19:39.979 --> 00:19:49.339
But yeah, we have a short-term analytics team and he had led analytics services,

00:19:50.060 --> 00:19:56.540
part of IT, kind of being that arm to help out our term training and stuff like that. And

00:19:56.540 --> 00:20:00.699
he looked over my shoulder one day and was just like, hey, I see you messing around with VBA.

00:20:00.699 --> 00:20:06.540
Have you ever heard of R? And I was just like, no, I've never heard of R. I was someone that

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:13.420
if I ever had to find the max in a vector, I was creating my own algorithm

00:20:14.459 --> 00:20:21.099
look for a max. I didn't realize people use the form, just max in Excel and use max in R.

00:20:21.099 --> 00:20:27.739
I was like, whoa, you already have half of the problem solved for you. Yeah. So from physics,

00:20:27.739 --> 00:20:33.979
I was learning C, Fortran, Python, and I got into a business and I was like, what is...

00:20:33.979 --> 00:20:42.300
Excel was a way for me to do data entry in a lab and then take that back and write a report.

00:20:42.300 --> 00:20:48.300
I never had thought that someone could build a full model in Excel or... I didn't know

00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:53.500
what SQL was. I was like, what is this? So I learned all of that and data science wasn't

00:20:53.500 --> 00:21:00.060
like a degree or a program when I went to college. So it was something that I happened into

00:21:00.060 --> 00:21:05.339
because I kind of really liked simulations. Like that was what I wanted to do. I didn't even want

00:21:05.339 --> 00:21:13.099
necessarily want to do physics. I was like concentrating in engineering, but had a CAD minor

